comments.body:
@mheon @ashley-cui @mtrmac PTAL  Especially the git hackery.  The branch says it needs updating, I don't think we should, but I'm not sure.

Here's my git hackery steps:

git checkout -b bump-1.33.2 c36ab60ca472e182e3dcd0d51df3f383b108a665
{change files}
git add {files}
git commit -m "Bump to v1.33.2" -s
{change version file, define/types.go]
git add {files}
git commit -m "Bump to v1.33.3-dev" -s
git rebase bump-1.33.2 main
git push -u TomSweeneyRedHat bump-1.33.2

Then in GitHub, opened the PR after reviewing.

@mtrmac @Luap99 @flouthoc thanks for the comments and suggestions.  Your example with x above Mirek is what I was hoping to do.  

I was hoping to avoid creating yet another branch and just pull a fast one, but often times fast ones aren't the best.  I'll go with the consensus and will whip up a branch.   Thanks all.

If nothing else, I enjoyed the git gymnastics of this one, I learned a bit in the process.
